  "prompt": "What is the definition of current?",
  "response": "In the context of physics and electrical engineering, **current** is defined as the flow of electric charge through a conductor or circuit. It represents the rate at which electric charge passes a given point in a circuit and is typically measured in amperes (A). \n\nMathematically, current (I) can be expressed as:\n\n\\[ \nI = \\frac{Q}{t} \n\\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( I \\) is the current in amperes,\n- \\( Q \\) is the electric charge in coulombs,\n- \\( t \\) is the time in seconds over which the charge flows.\n\nCurrent can be classified into two main types:\n\n1. **Direct Current (DC)** - where the electric charge flows in one direction.\n2. **Alternating Current (AC)** - where the electric charge changes direction periodically.\n\nIn a broader context, the term \"current\" can also refer to the flow of any medium, such as water currents in rivers or air currents in the atmosphere.",
